	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />CA65 isn't that bad. As I see it, it abstracts the process of "where your code goes" into a nice neat config file. With most assemblers, you must set the program counter or pad in numerous places. In CA65, your config file specifies memory areas and segments, with starting addresses (the program counter) and whether to fill to the specified size. It's really the same thing, only now your source code just fills segments specified by your config file. So, if you understand a normal assembler, there's really nothing stopping you from using CA65. It took me maybe an afternoon of hair pulling, now it is my favorite assembler.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


